thread.title: Kiwi falls against stronger greenback

author: news.com.au
title: Kiwi falls against stronger greenback
text:
THE New Zealand dollar has fallen as traders continued to wind back bets that the US Federal Reserve will raise interest rates as soon as September, helping lift Wall Street stocks.
THE kiwi dropped to 64.34 US cents as at 5pm in Wellington from 64.93 cents in late trading on Wednesday.
The trade-weighted index fell to 69.67 from 70.12 on Wednesday. New York Federal Reserve chief William Dudley stoked speculation the Fed won't rush to raise interest rates, saying starting the normalisation process at the September FOMC meeting "seems less compelling to me than it was a few weeks ago". Both the Australian and New Zealand dollars fell as the greenback rose. "They are both struggling - there are plenty of people looking to sell into any rallies," said Mark Johnson, senior dealer at OMF. "Both currencies succumbed to US dollar strength overnight." The New Zealand dollar slipped to 90.57 Australian cents at 5pm from 91.03 cents on Wednesday, to 77.14 yen from 77.63 yen and to 4.1210 yuan from 4.1627 yuan, but firmed to 56.65 euro cents from 56.49 cents.
